nfronts neoliberalism and gang violence. In Colombia's El Man, in turn, rapid urbanization and drug cartels are the central concerns, whereas corruption and the political machinations of the state feature most prominently in the television and web series Capitán Centroamérica. While the Latin American superhero genre may be superficially characterized by low budgets and kitsch aesthetics, it also poses profound challenges to the social, political, and economic status quo. Covering a wide variety of media bookended by wrestling films from the early 1960s and multimedia productions from the 2010s, Capitán Latinoamérica offers a comprehensive introduction to, and assessment of, the state of the superhero in Latin America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aInternet televisionxHistory and criticismzLatin America. 0aInternet televisionzLatin AmericaxHistory and criticism. 0aInternet television-Latin America-History and criticism. 0aSuperhero filmsxHistory and criticismzLatin America. 0aSuperhero filmszLatin AmericaxHistory and criticism. 0aSuperhero films-Latin America-History and criticism. 0aSuperhero television programsxHistory and criticismzLatin America. 0aSuperhero television programszLatin AmericaxHistory and criticism. 0aSuperhero television programs-Latin America-History and criticism. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438480169423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438480169/original  